Accident Severity Prediction for Airlines¶

1. Introduction¶

The aim of this project is to implement Machine Learning models that can be used to anticipate and classify the severity of an airplane accident based on data collected from past incidents. The aviation industry, can utilize these models to predict the severity of airplane accidents caused due to various factors and, correspondingly, have a plan of action to minimize the risk associated with them.

2. Data¶

The dataset consists of two files:

  • train.csv This is the training data which has 10000 rows and 12 columns.

  • test.csv The test data contains 2500 observations and 11 columns.

Description of columns¶

  • Accident_ID: unique id assigned to each row
  • Accident_Type_Code: the type of accident (factor, not numeric)
  • Cabin_Temperature: the last recorded temperature before the incident, measured in degrees Fahrenheit
  • Turbulence_In_gforces: the recorded/estimated turbulence experienced during the accident
  • Control_Metric: an estimation of how much control the pilot had during the incident given the factors at play
  • Total_Safety_Complaints: number of complaints from mechanics prior to the accident
  • Days_Since_Inspection: how long the plane went without inspection before the incident
  • Safety_Score: a measure of how safe the plane was deemed to be
  • Violations: number of violations that the aircraft received during inspections
  • Severity (Target variable): a description (4 level factor) on the severity of the crash

3. Methodology¶

First we obtain the data from the given CSV files. Then, we perform an EDA - Exploratory Data Analysis to analyze the Features and Target variables. The next step is to perform data preprocessing to make the data amenable to further analysis and modeling. We then use some Machine Learning algorithms to perform Training and then make predictions on the Validation data. The model with the best accuracy is selected to perform predictions on the Test dataset. The final results are copied to a csv file for submission.

It is a good practice to standardize the variables by removing the mean and scaling to unit variance. The reason is, if a feature has a variance that is of magnitude much larger that others, it might dominate the objective function and make the estimator unable to learn from other features correctly as expected. We standardize the input X and the test data as well.

In [26]:
X=StandardScaler().fit(X).transform(X.astype(float))

K Nearest Neighbors¶

We first determine the best k value based on maximum accuracy score, for k values ranging from 3 to 29.

In [29]:
acc_list = []
for k in range(3,30):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = k)
    knn.fit(X_train,Y_train)
    knn_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    #acc_array[i-1] = round(accuracy_score(knn_pred,Y_test)*100,2)
    acc_list.append(round(accuracy_score(knn_pred,Y_test)*100,2))
#acc_list
max_acc = max(acc_list)
optimum_k = acc_list.index(max(acc_list)) + 3
print('The maximum accuracy',max_acc, 'is obtained for k =',optimum_k)

The maximum accuracy 65.7 is obtained for k = 14

We choose k = 14 as this gives us the best accuracy. We then fit the model on Training and predict on the Validation data.

In [30]:
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 14) 
knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)  
knn_pred = knn.predict(X_test)  
knn_acc = round(accuracy_score(knn_pred,Y_test) * 100, 2)
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=22) 
cv_knn=cross_val_score(knn,X,Y,cv=10,scoring='accuracy')

print('The accuracy of the K Nearest Neighbors Classifier is',knn_acc)
print('The cross validated score for K Nearest Neighbors Classifier is:',round(cv_knn.mean()*100,2))

The accuracy of the K Nearest Neighbors Classifier is 65.7
The cross validated score for K Nearest Neighbors Classifier is: 67.46
